    "50618811": {
      "title": "Photochemistry of ozone formation in Atlanta, GA: Models and measurements",
      "abstract": "Chemical measurements made during an air pollution event in Atlanta, GA have been compared with results from several photochemical simulations. Measurements included Os, primary reactive organic gases (ROG), aldehydes, PAN, total reactive nitrogen (NO,,) and HzOz, with vertical profiles for primary ROG. Photochemical models using two different chemical representations and a range of assumptions about winds, vertical mixing and emissions were used to simulate the event. Results show that assumptions about vertical mixing can cause a variation in simulated surface concentrations of primary hydrocarbons of a factor of two or more. A tendency to underestimate isoprene was found in comparison with measured vertical profiles. The models tend to overestimate concentrations of HCHO, H,02 and PAN in comparison with measurements. Peak 0s and concurrent NO, from helicopter measurements was used as a basis for evaluating individual model scenarios. Scenarios were developed with different Op-NO,-ROG sensitivity, but only the NO,-sensitive scenarios are consistent with measured 09, NO, and isoprene. Key word index: Ozone, nitrogen oxides, hydrocarbons, photochemical smog, hydrogen, peroxide."
    }
  }
}